:Class ADOC
‚ćĚ Automated Documentation Generation
‚ćĚ ----------------------------------
‚ćĚ ### Overview
‚ćĚ This class is useful for analysing one or more scripts and/or namespaces for
‚ćĚ documentation purposes. Note that the documentation should be useful for
‚ćĚ the **user** of a class, not the designer/programmer of a class.\\
‚ćĚ ### Information collected from a class or namespace:\\
‚ćĚ * Creating a single HTML page with all available information, including any
‚ćĚ   injected documentation.
‚ćĚ   If you are reading this you are looking at what `ADOC` produces when processing itself.
‚ćĚ * Getting a list of public methods, properties and fields (classes and interfaces)
‚ćĚ   or functions, operators and variables (namespaces).
‚ćĚ * Same as before but with more detailed information.\\
‚ćĚ The first option is by far the most powerful and popular option, as it allows you
‚ćĚ to add additional information to scripts and also ordinary namespaces:
‚ćĚ all "leading comments" are treated as special information.\\
‚ćĚ Leading comments are the lines after the header line (and possibly the definition of
‚ćĚ local variables and access statements like `:Access...`) that start with a lamp (`‚ćĚ`)
‚ćĚ symbol followed by either a space or another `‚ćĚ`. The first line that does not start with
‚ćĚ a lamp symbol defines the end of a leading comment, although lines with `‚ćĚ‚ćĚ` are ignored.\\
‚ćĚ You can use Markdown to format the documentation. See [Markup syntax](#) for details
‚ćĚ of how to do this.\\
‚ćĚ There is a workaround available for non-scripted namespaces.\\
‚ćĚ Note that `ADOC` can handle subclasses. For example, `ADOC` itself comes with a subclass
‚ćĚ called `Demo`. Therefore, both `Browse` and `List` will process `ADOC.Demo`. However, you
‚ćĚ cannot make use of `ADOC.Demo` when it is run as a user command.
‚ćĚ ### `ADOC` as a user command
‚ćĚ The following examples assume that you have `MyClass`, `MyInterface` and `MyNamespace`
‚ćĚ in your workspace.
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ List all methods, fields and properties
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ of the public interface:
‚ćĚ       ]ADoc MyClass -summary
‚ćĚ
‚ćĚ
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ Same but with more details:
‚ćĚ       ]ADoc MyClass -summary=full
‚ćĚ
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ Produce a full blown document with leading
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ comments and the public interface and view
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ it with your default browser:
‚ćĚ       ]ADoc MyClass
‚ćĚ
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ Same but for several objects:
‚ćĚ       ]ADoc MyClass MyInterface MyNamespace
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ ### Advanced features
‚ćĚ You can use advanced features by using the API via `‚éēSE.ADOC` introduced in version 7.0.0\\
‚ćĚ The advanced  features are documented in a separate document that can be viewed
‚ćĚ by calling `‚éēSE.ADOC.ShowDocumentation 2`. (Passing a 1 as `‚ćĶ` would view the same as `]ADOC -???`)\\
‚ćĚ ### What `ADOC` considers to be documentation
‚ćĚ Note that comments are recognized only if and as long they follow
‚ćĚ the "header": the top of a script, functions and operators, headers and field
‚ćĚ definitions **after** removing empty lines and any
‚ćĚ lines of code that carry an `:Access ...` statement.
‚ćĚ #### Special case :Field
‚ćĚ `:Field` is handled differently because there is no concept of a "header"; it's
‚ćĚ just a single line, and until version 5.3 the only thing you could do was to add
‚ćĚ a comment to the right of a `:Field` definition.\\
‚ćĚ Since 5.4 however any further comment lines are considered part of the `:Field`
‚ćĚ documentation until either two empty lines are detected, or something like a  function,
‚ćĚ operator, property, another field definition etc.
‚ćĚ #### Excluding a line
‚ćĚ In case you want to exclude a particular line from the leading comments
‚ćĚ use two lamps (`‚ćĚ‚ćĚ`) at the beginning of the line. This will **not** break
‚ćĚ the link with comments further down the line. For example:
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ This line appears in the `ADOC` documentation.
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ‚ćĚ This line doesn't appears in the `ADOC` documentation.
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ This line also appears in the `ADOC` documentation,.
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ ### :Require
‚ćĚ With version 15.0 Dyalog has introduced the `:Require` keyword for defining
‚ćĚ dependencies.\\
‚ćĚ Since this keyword lives outside classes and namespaces while the older --- and deprecated ---
‚ćĚ synonym `‚ćĚ‚ąá:require` lives inside classes and namespaces we have a conflict here: `ADOC` can't
‚ćĚ report what's not in the source code, so there is no way to overcome this. 
‚ćĚ ### Markup syntax
‚ćĚ You can use Markdown, a simplified markup language, within the comment sections of public
‚ćĚ functions and the so-called leading comments of scripts. `ADOC` uses the APLTree class
‚ćĚ [`MarkAPL`](https://github.com/aplteam/MarkAPL "MarkAPL on GitHub") to convert the
‚ćĚ Markdown to HTML.\\
‚ćĚ `ADOC` itself can be used as an example: it uses all of the markup available, most importantly:
‚ćĚ * Headers
‚ćĚ * Bulleted lists
‚ćĚ   1. Ordered lists
‚ćĚ   1. Unordered lists
‚ćĚ * APL code
‚ćĚ   * Inline APL code
‚ćĚ   * APL code blocks
‚ćĚ * Tables
‚ćĚ * Paragraphs\\
‚ćĚ But there is no limitation: every feature that is available in MarkAPL can be used and will
‚ćĚ be processed by `ADOC`. Therefore you can read up on how to do the mark up in the
‚ćĚ [MarkAPL cheat sheet](http://download.aplteam.com/MarkAPL_CheatSheet.html) or in the laborious
‚ćĚ [full MarkAPL documentation](http://download.aplteam.com/MarkAPL.html).\\
‚ćĚ There are however two additional features available:
‚ćĚ 1. You can insert a line break (`<br />`) by having a single backslash character (`\`) at the
‚ćĚ    end of a line.
‚ćĚ 1. You can enforce a new paragraph by adding two backslashes at the end of a line.\\
‚ćĚ    This can be useful when you need to document plenty of method calls etc but want to avoid
‚ćĚ    a large number of empty lines.\\
‚ćĚ Note that these are ADOC features, not MarkAPL features.
‚ćĚ #### Leading comments in functions and operators
‚ćĚ Headers within the leading comments in public functions and operators are limited to level six.
‚ćĚ If you define a different level then it will be converted to level 6 anyway. Therefore, you may
‚ćĚ well define level-1 headers for better readability.
‚ćĚ for better readability.\\
‚ćĚ ### Namespaces
‚ćĚ #### Overview
‚ćĚ Since version 6.0 `ADOC` supports not only scripted namespaces but also normal namespaces.
‚ćĚ `ADOC` can process any namespace that can be saved by Link.\\
‚ćĚ #### Public & private functions, operators & variables
‚ćĚ By default all functions, operators and variables are public.\\
‚ćĚ In namespaces `ADOC` searches for a function `Public`.\\
‚ćĚ If such a function exists it will be expected to return a vector of text vectors.
‚ćĚ These are interpreted as the names of all public functions, operators and variables.\\
‚ćĚ This means that by implementing this function you can define what is public and what isn't.\\
‚ćĚ #### Scripted versus normal namespaces
‚ćĚ `ADOC` will process leading comment lines in a scripted namespace in the same way
‚ćĚ as it does with classes and interfaces.\\
‚ćĚ However, in normal namespaces there can be no "leading" comments. As a replacement you can
‚ćĚ create a variable: a vector of text vectors. The name is by convention `ADOC_Doc`.\\
‚ćĚ The variable can contain the markdown as is, without the leading `‚ćĚ` symbol; this makes editing easier.\\
‚ćĚ For example:
‚ćĚ ```
‚ćĚ ‚ćĚ Variable
‚ćĚ 'Temp'#.‚éēNS''
‚ćĚ #.Temp.ADOC_Doc‚Üź'My comment from line 1' '' '* This' '* That'
‚ćĚ #.Temp.‚éēFX'r‚ÜźHello' 'r‚Üź''Word'''
‚ćĚ ]ADoc #.Temp
‚ćĚ ```
‚ćĚ Prior to version 6.0 `Browse` accepted `ADOC_Doc` as the name of a function within an ordinary namespace;
‚ćĚ this is no longer supported. Replace the function by a variable (vector of character vectors) with the
‚ćĚ same name.
‚ćĚ ### Tatin packages
‚ćĚ The user command is able to deal with reference(s) to Tatin package(s) provided as argument.\\
‚ćĚ For example:
‚ćĚ ```
‚ćĚ       ]LoadPackages [tatin]MakeHelpers
‚ćĚ ...
‚ćĚ       ‚éē‚Üź#.MakeHelpers
‚ćĚ #._tatin.aplteam_MakeHelpers_0_7_0.API
‚ćĚ       ]ADoc #._tatin.aplteam_MakeHelpers_0_7_0.API   ‚ćĚ Works
‚ćĚ       ]ADoc #._tatin.aplteam_MakeHelpers_0_7_0       ‚ćĚ Works as well
‚ćĚ       ]ADoc #.MakeHelpers                            ‚ćĚ Works too
‚ćĚ ```
‚ćĚ
‚ćĚ The caption always becomes `<group>_<name>_<major_minor_patch> (Namespace)` in these cases.
‚ćĚ ### Reserved names
‚ćĚ Since version 3.0 `ADOC` looks for a number of fixed names. If a function or a variable
‚ćĚ with such a name is found, the contents of the variable or the result of that function is used.\\
‚ćĚ The syntax rules are fixed: if such a function does not honor the syntax rules it will
‚ćĚ fail. However, since all calls are trapped that won't stop `ADOC` from producing a result.\\
‚ćĚ Functions must be niladic traditional functions marked as:
‚ćĚ
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ :Access Public Shared
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ and they must return a result.\\
‚ćĚ Note that variables make no sense in class scripts since they cannot be public.
‚ćĚ `History` and `Copyright` might be nested vectors of character vectors while `Version` might be a simple
‚ćĚ character vector or a nested vector of length two or three.\\
‚ćĚ #### Copyright
‚ćĚ Must be/return a vector of character vectors.\\
‚ćĚ #### History
‚ćĚ If this exists, it must be one of the following:
‚ćĚ * A function that returns either a simple text vector or a vector of text vectors with markdown
‚ćĚ   (now deprecated).
‚ćĚ * A function that returns **no** result and contains markdown as comments.\\
‚ćĚ * A variable that is a nested vector of character vectors.\\
‚ćĚ #### Version
‚ćĚ Must return one of:
‚ćĚ * A simple character vector like `1.2.3`
‚ćĚ * A nested vector of length two:
‚ćĚ   1. A character vector with version information, for example "1.2.3" or "17.0.1+13245"
‚ćĚ   1. A character vector representing a date, for example "2009-01-01"
‚ćĚ * A nested vector of length three:
‚ćĚ   1. The name, for example `ADOC`
‚ćĚ   1. A character vector with version information
‚ćĚ   1. A character vector representing a date\\
‚ćĚ For example, a function returning this:
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ ('1.2.3' '2009-06-01') ‚Üź‚Üí 1‚Üď#.MyNameSpace.Version
‚ćĚ ~~~
‚ćĚ lets `ADOC` produce this information:
‚ćĚ "Version 1.2.3 from 2009-06-01"\\
‚ćĚ ### Specialties
‚ćĚ #### :Include
‚ćĚ Since version 1.3, `ADOC` is processing `:Include`d namespaces.\\
‚ćĚ This means that included stuff is "imported" in the first place, then the result
‚ćĚ is analyzed.\\
‚ćĚ Author: Kai Jaeger ‚čĄ <http://github.com/aplteam/ADOC>\\
‚ćĚ Homepage: <https://github.com/aplteam/ADOC>

    ‚éēIO‚Üź1 ‚čĄ ‚éēML‚Üź3

    ‚ąá r‚ÜźVersion;v
      :Access Public shared
      :If 0<##.‚éēNC'TatinVars.CONFIG'
          v‚Üź(‚éēJSON‚ć†('Dialect' 'JSON5')‚äĘ##.TatinVars.CONFIG).version
      :ElseIf 0<##.##.‚éēNC'TatinVars.CONFIG'
          v‚Üź(‚éēJSON‚ć†('Dialect' 'JSON5')‚äĘ##.##.TatinVars.CONFIG).version
      :Else
     ‚ćĚ When a script is not loaded with Tatin, there will be no namespace `TatinVars`.
     ‚ćĚ In such cases we cannot provide a version number, so we return an empty char vector
